UPDATE public.lessons SET content = E'# Variables: var, let & const — Mastering JavaScript Data Storage\n\n---\n\n## 1. Introduction\n\nVariables are containers that store data values. In JavaScript, HOW you declare a variable matters enormously — it affects scope, hoisting behavior, and whether the value can be changed. Choosing the wrong declaration keyword is one of the most common sources of JavaScript bugs.\n\nJavaScript has three ways to declare variables:\n- `var` — the original (pre-2015), avoid in modern code\n- `let` — the modern standard for values that change\n- `const` — the modern standard for values that should not change\n\n> **Industry Reality:** In production codebases at companies like Razorpay and Freshworks, you will NEVER see `var`. Every modern JavaScript style guide (Airbnb, Google, StandardJS) mandates `const` by default and `let` when reassignment is needed. `var` is a legacy relic.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Learning Objectives\n\nBy the end of this lesson you will be able to:\n- Declare variables using `var`, `let`, and `const` correctly\n- Explain the difference in scoping behavior (function vs block)\n- Understand hoisting and the Temporal Dead Zone (TDZ)\n- Explain why `var` causes bugs in loops and async code\n- Use the correct declaration in every scenario\n- Understand that `const` does NOT make objects immutable\n- Pass JavaScript interview questions about scope and hoisting\n\n---\n\n## 3. Concept Explanation\n\n### Beginner Level — Declaring Variables\n\n```javascript\n// The three ways to create a variable\nvar   courseName = "HTML5";      // Old way — avoid\nlet   userScore  = 150;          // Modern — for values that change\nconst MAX_XP     = 10000;        // Modern — for values that stay the same\n\n// Naming rules:\n// ✅ Starts with letter, _, or $\n// ✅ Can contain letters, digits, _, $\n// ❌ Cannot start with digit\n// ❌ Cannot be a reserved word (if, for, function, class...)\n\n// Naming conventions:\nconst firstName     = "Alice";          // camelCase for variables\nconst MAX_ATTEMPTS  = 3;               // SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE for constants\nconst UserProfile   = class {};        // PascalCase for classes\nconst _privateVar   = "internal";      // _ prefix for "private" convention\n```\n\n### Intermediate Level — Scope: The Critical Difference\n\nScope defines WHERE in your code a variable is visible (accessible).\n\n**`var` — Function Scope**\n```javascript\nfunction showVarScope() {\n  var x = 10;\n\n  if (true) {\n    var y = 20;       // var is FUNCTION scoped\n    console.log(x);  // 10 — accessible\n    console.log(y);  // 20 — accessible\n  }\n\n  console.log(x);    // 10 — still accessible\n  console.log(y);    // 20 — STILL accessible! (leaks out of if block)\n}\n\nshowVarScope();\nconsole.log(x); // ReferenceError — function scope ends here\nconsole.log(y); // ReferenceError — function scope ends here\n```\n\n**`let` and `const` — Block Scope**\n```javascript\nfunction showLetScope() {\n  let x = 10;\n\n  if (true) {\n    let y  = 20;      // let is BLOCK scoped (block = anything inside {})\n    const z = 30;     // const is also BLOCK scoped\n\n    console.log(x);   // 10 — accessible (outer block)\n    console.log(y);   // 20 — accessible (same block)\n    console.log(z);   // 30 — accessible (same block)\n  }\n\n  console.log(x);    // 10 — still accessible\n  console.log(y);    // ReferenceError — y is not defined (block ended)\n  console.log(z);    // ReferenceError — z is not defined (block ended)\n}\n```\n\n### Advanced Level — Hoisting & The Temporal Dead Zone\n\n**Hoisting** = JavaScript moves variable declarations to the top of their scope at compile time.\n\n```javascript\n// What YOU write:\nconsole.log(a);  // undefined (not error!)\nvar a = 5;\nconsole.log(a);  // 5\n\n// What JavaScript SEES (after hoisting):\nvar a;           // Declaration hoisted to top\nconsole.log(a);  // undefined (declared but not initialized)\na = 5;           // Assignment stays here\nconsole.log(a);  // 5\n```\n\n**`let` and `const` have a Temporal Dead Zone (TDZ):**\n```javascript\nconsole.log(b);  // ReferenceError: Cannot access ''b'' before initialization\nlet b = 5;\nconsole.log(b);  // 5\n\nconsole.log(c);  // ReferenceError: Cannot access ''c'' before initialization\nconst c = 10;\n```\n\n> The TDZ exists from the start of the block until the `let`/`const` declaration is reached. Accessing within the TDZ throws a ReferenceError — which is BETTER than `var`''s silent `undefined`.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Visual Learning\n\n```\nSCOPE VISUALIZATION\n\nGlobal Scope\n│  var globalVar = "visible everywhere"\n│  let globalLet = "also global"\n│\n└── function myFunction() {       ← Function scope\n    │  var funcVar = "only in this function"\n    │  let funcLet = "only in this function"\n    │\n    └── if (condition) {           ← Block scope\n        │  var blockVar = "visible to function scope!"\n        │  let blockLet = "ONLY in this block"\n        │  const blockConst = "ONLY in this block"\n        }\n        // blockLet not accessible here\n        // blockVar IS accessible here (var leaks!)\n    }\n// funcVar not accessible here\n\n\nHOISTING COMPARISON\n\n     var              let/const\n  ┌─────────┐       ┌─────────────┐\n  │HOISTED  │       │HOISTED but  │\n  │as       │       │in Temporal  │\n  │undefined│       │Dead Zone    │\n  └─────────┘       └─────────────┘\n  Access before:    Access before:\n  undefined (ok)    ReferenceError\n  (silently wrong)  (loudly correct)\n\n\nCONST AND MUTABILITY\n\n  const x = 42;\n  x = 100;          ← TypeError: Assignment to constant variable\n\n  const obj = { name: "Alice" };\n  obj.name = "Bob"; ← ✅ ALLOWED (mutation, not reassignment)\n  obj = {};         ← TypeError: Assignment to constant variable\n\n  const arr = [1, 2, 3];\n  arr.push(4);      ← ✅ ALLOWED (mutation)\n  arr = [5, 6];     ← TypeError: Assignment to constant variable\n\n  Think of const as a pointer that cannot be redirected,\n  NOT as a deep freeze of the value.\n```\n\n---\n\n## 5. Syntax Reference\n\n```javascript\n// DECLARATION PATTERNS\n\n// 1. Declare and initialize\nconst PI     = 3.14159;\nlet   count  = 0;\n\n// 2. Declare without initializing (let only)\nlet score;              // undefined\nscore = 100;            // initialize later\n\n// 3. Destructuring assignment\nconst [first, second, ...rest] = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5];\nconst { name, age, city = "Mumbai" } = user;  // city has default\nconst { name: userName } = user;              // rename to userName\n\n// 4. Multiple declarations\nlet a = 1, b = 2, c = 3;          // Allowed but discouraged\nconst x = 1;                       // Preferred: one per line\nconst y = 2;\nconst z = 3;\n\n// 5. Swapping without temp variable\nlet p = 1, q = 2;\n[p, q] = [q, p];\nconsole.log(p, q); // 2 1\n\n// CORRECT declaration choice:\nconst MAX_RETRY = 3;           // number that never changes → const\nlet   retryCount = 0;          // number that changes       → let\nconst config = { debug: true }; // object reference is fixed → const\nconst users = [];               // array reference is fixed  → const\n```\n\n---\n\n## 6. Multiple Code Examples\n\n### Example 1 — The Famous var-in-Loop Bug\n```javascript\n// THE BUG — Using var in a loop with setTimeout\nfor (var i = 0; i < 3; i++) {\n  setTimeout(() => {\n    console.log(i); // 3, 3, 3  ← WRONG!\n  }, 100);\n}\n// Why? var i is function-scoped. By the time setTimeout fires,\n// the loop has finished and i = 3 for ALL callbacks.\n\n// FIX 1 — Use let (block scoped, new i per iteration)\nfor (let i = 0; i < 3; i++) {\n  setTimeout(() => {\n    console.log(i); // 0, 1, 2  ← CORRECT!\n  }, 100);\n}\n\n// FIX 2 — Use IIFE to capture i (old-school fix, now use let)\nfor (var i = 0; i < 3; i++) {\n  ((capturedI) => {\n    setTimeout(() => console.log(capturedI), 100); // 0, 1, 2\n  })(i);\n}\n```\n\n### Example 2 — const with Objects and Arrays\n```javascript\n// const prevents REASSIGNMENT, not MUTATION\nconst user = {\n  name: "Alice",\n  xp:   1000,\n  courses: []\n};\n\n// These all WORK — we are mutating, not reassigning\nuser.name = "Bob";              // ✅ Change property\nuser.xp   += 50;               // ✅ Modify property\nuser.courses.push("HTML5");    // ✅ Modify nested array\ndelete user.xp;                // ✅ Delete property\n\n// This FAILS — we are trying to reassign the const\nuser = { name: "Charlie" };    // ❌ TypeError\n\n// How to truly make an object immutable\nconst frozen = Object.freeze({ name: "Alice", xp: 1000 });\nfrozen.name = "Bob";  // Silent failure in non-strict mode\n                       // TypeError in strict mode\nconsole.log(frozen.name); // "Alice" — unchanged\n\n// Note: Object.freeze is shallow (nested objects not frozen)\nconst deepObj = Object.freeze({ user: { name: "Alice" } });\ndeepObj.user.name = "Bob";  // This WORKS (nested object not frozen)\n```\n\n### Example 3 — Real-World Code Patterns\n```javascript\n// React component using const/let correctly\nfunction UserDashboard({ userId }) {\n  // Constants — never change during component life\n  const BASE_URL  = process.env.REACT_APP_API_URL;\n  const MAX_COURSES = 6;\n\n  // State (managed by React, but declare let for local)\n  const [user,    setUser]    = useState(null);   // const because we never reassign [user, setUser]\n  const [loading, setLoading] = useState(true);\n  const [error,   setError]   = useState(null);\n\n  // Computed values\n  const displayName = user ? `${user.firstName} ${user.lastName}` : "Guest";\n  const isAdmin     = user?.role === "admin";\n\n  // Let for values that accumulate\n  useEffect(() => {\n    let cancelled = false;  // let because we set it to true on cleanup\n\n    async function loadUser() {\n      try {\n        const response = await fetch(`${BASE_URL}/users/${userId}`);\n        const data     = await response.json();\n        if (!cancelled) setUser(data);\n      } catch (err) {\n        if (!cancelled) setError(err.message);\n      } finally {\n        if (!cancelled) setLoading(false);\n      }\n    }\n\n    loadUser();\n    return () => { cancelled = true; }; // cleanup\n  }, [userId]);\n}\n```\n\n### Example 4 — Scope in Real Application Code\n```javascript\n// Demonstrating scope in a shopping cart implementation\nconst cart = [];\n\nfunction addToCart(product) {\n  const item = {           // const — this reference never changes\n    id:       product.id,\n    name:     product.name,\n    quantity: 1,\n    price:    product.price,\n  };\n\n  const existing = cart.find(i => i.id === product.id);\n\n  if (existing) {\n    existing.quantity += 1;  // Mutate object property\n  } else {\n    cart.push(item);         // Mutate array\n  }\n\n  // This let is block-scoped to addToCart\n  let total = 0;\n  for (const cartItem of cart) {   // const in for...of — new binding each iteration\n    total += cartItem.price * cartItem.quantity;\n  }\n\n  return total;\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n## 7. Try It Yourself\n\n### Exercise 1 — Scope Prediction\nPredict the output of each console.log BEFORE running:\n```javascript\nvar a = 1;\nlet b = 2;\nconst c = 3;\n\n{\n  var a = 10;    // Same variable (var is function/global scoped)\n  let b = 20;   // New variable (block scoped)\n  const c = 30; // New variable (block scoped)\n  console.log(a, b, c); // ???\n}\n\nconsole.log(a, b, c); // ???\n```\n\n### Exercise 2 — Fix the Bug\n```javascript\n// Fix this code so it prints 0, 1, 2 (not 3, 3, 3)\nconst callbacks = [];\nfor (var i = 0; i < 3; i++) {\n  callbacks.push(() => console.log(i));\n}\ncallbacks.forEach(fn => fn());\n// Currently prints: 3, 3, 3\n// Your fix:\n```\n\n### Exercise 3 — const or let?\n```javascript\n// For each variable below, decide: should it be const or let?\n// Give your reason.\n\n___ PI = 3.14;\n___ userAge = 25;           // Will change on birthday\n___ API_ENDPOINT = "/api";  // Never changes\n___ score = 0;               // Increases as user plays\n___ users = [];              // Array that gets items pushed\n___ MAX_SCORE = 100;         // Never changes\n___ currentUser = null;      // Will be set after login\n```\n\n---\n\n## 8. Common Mistakes\n\n### Mistake 1 — Using var in modern code\n```javascript\n// WRONG — avoid var entirely\nfor (var i = 0; i < items.length; i++) { ... }  // i leaks outside loop\n\n// CORRECT\nfor (let i = 0; i < items.length; i++) { ... }  // i stays in loop\n```\n\n### Mistake 2 — Thinking const makes objects immutable\n```javascript\n// WRONG assumption\nconst config = { debug: true };\nconfig.debug = false; // This WORKS — const does not prevent this!\n\n// If you need immutability, use Object.freeze\nconst config = Object.freeze({ debug: true });\nconfig.debug = false; // Silently fails (or error in strict mode)\n```\n\n### Mistake 3 — Not using default values\n```javascript\n// WRONG — potential undefined errors\nconst { name, age } = user;\nconsole.log(age.toString()); // TypeError if age is undefined\n\n// CORRECT — provide defaults\nconst { name, age = 0 } = user;\nconsole.log(age.toString()); // "0" if age is missing\n```\n\n### Mistake 4 — Declaring loop variable with const in for\n```javascript\n// WRONG — const cannot be reassigned (i++ fails)\nfor (const i = 0; i < 5; i++) { ... } // TypeError!\n\n// CORRECT — use let for counter\nfor (let i = 0; i < 5; i++) { ... }\n\n// BUT const works in for...of and for...in\nfor (const item of items) { ... }   // New binding each iteration\nfor (const key in obj) { ... }      // New binding each iteration\n```\n\n---\n\n## 9. Best Practices\n\n1. **Default to `const`** — use `let` only when you know the value will change\n2. **Never use `var`** — no exceptions in modern JavaScript\n3. **One variable per declaration line** — easier to read, debug, and git-diff\n4. **Use descriptive names** — `userFirstName` not `fn`, `totalPrice` not `tp`\n5. **Declare variables at the top of their scope** — prevents temporal dead zone surprises\n6. **Use SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE for true constants** — `const MAX_RETRY_ATTEMPTS = 3`\n7. **Destructure early for object/array access** — more readable\n\n---\n\n## 10. Real-World Usage\n\n### In Production React Code\n```javascript\n// Pattern at companies like Swiggy, Ola, etc.\nconst API_BASE    = process.env.REACT_APP_API_URL;  // Environment constant\nconst RETRY_LIMIT = 3;                               // Config constant\n\nexport function useCart() {\n  const [items, setItems]       = useState([]);    // State — const because ref stable\n  const [loading, setLoading]   = useState(false);\n\n  const addItem = useCallback((product) => {         // const — function ref\n    setItems(prev => {\n      const existing = prev.find(i => i.id === product.id); // const — single use\n      if (existing) {\n        return prev.map(i => i.id === product.id ? { ...i, qty: i.qty + 1 } : i);\n      }\n      return [...prev, { ...product, qty: 1 }];\n    });\n  }, []);\n\n  return { items, loading, addItem };\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n## 11. Interview Preparation\n\n**Q: What is hoisting in JavaScript?**\n> Hoisting is JavaScript''s behavior of moving declarations (not initializations) to the top of their scope before execution. `var` declarations are hoisted as `undefined`. `let`/`const` are hoisted but remain in the Temporal Dead Zone until their declaration line is reached.\n\n**Q: What is the Temporal Dead Zone?**\n> The TDZ is the period between the start of a `let`/`const` variable''s scope and its declaration line. Accessing a variable in the TDZ throws a `ReferenceError`. It exists to catch programming errors that `var`''s silent `undefined` would hide.\n\n**Q: Why does this code print 3, 3, 3 instead of 0, 1, 2?**\n```javascript\nfor (var i = 0; i < 3; i++) {\n  setTimeout(() => console.log(i), 0);\n}\n```\n> Because `var` is function-scoped, there is only ONE `i` variable shared across all iterations. By the time the setTimeout callbacks execute, the loop has completed and `i` is 3. Using `let` creates a new `i` binding for each iteration, so each callback captures its own copy.\n\n**Q: Does `const` make an object immutable?**\n> No. `const` prevents reassignment of the variable binding, but does not prevent mutation of the referenced object. You can still add/change/delete properties of a `const` object. Use `Object.freeze()` for shallow immutability.\n\n**Q: What is the difference between global scope and function scope?**\n> Global scope: variables accessible anywhere in the program. Function scope: variables declared inside a function are only accessible inside that function (and nested functions). `var` is function-scoped; `let`/`const` are block-scoped (any `{}`).\n\n---\n\n## 12. Knowledge Check\n\n1. What are the three ways to declare a variable in JavaScript?\n2. What is the difference between `let` and `const`?\n3. Can you change a property of a `const` object? Why?\n4. What does "hoisting" mean?\n5. What is the Temporal Dead Zone?\n6. Why does `var` in a for loop with setTimeout cause bugs?\n7. What scope does `var` have? What scope does `let` have?\n8. What is block scope and what defines a block?\n9. When should you use `let` over `const`?\n10. Is `const arr = []` followed by `arr.push(1)` valid JavaScript?\n\n---\n\n## 13. Coding Challenges\n\n### Easy — Variable Declaration Fixer\n```\nProblem: Rewrite the code replacing all var declarations with\nthe appropriate let or const.\n\nvar PI = 3.14;\nvar userName = "Alice";\nvar score = 0;\nvar MAX_SCORE = 100;\nvar items = [];\nfor (var i = 0; i < 5; i++) {\n  score += 10;\n}\n\nRules:\n- Values that should never change → const\n- Values that will change → let\n- Loop counters → let\n```\n\n### Medium — Scope Analyzer\n```\nProblem: Given a code string, identify all variable declarations and\nfor each one output: name, type (var/let/const), scope (global/function/block).\n\nInput:\n"var x = 1;\nfunction foo() {\n  let y = 2;\n  if (true) {\n    const z = 3;\n  }\n}"\n\nOutput:\n[\n  { name: "x", type: "var", scope: "global" },\n  { name: "y", type: "let", scope: "function:foo" },\n  { name: "z", type: "const", scope: "block:if" }\n]\n```\n\n### Hard — Implement Block Scope (Conceptual)\n```\nProblem: Before let/const existed, developers faked block scope using IIFEs.\nConvert modern let/const code to ES5 using IIFEs and closures.\n\nModern (ES6):\nfor (let i = 0; i < 3; i++) {\n  setTimeout(() => console.log(i), 100);\n}\n\nES5 equivalent (your task):\n// Convert using IIFE so that 0, 1, 2 is logged correctly\n// without using let or const\n```\n\n---\n\n## 14. Mini Project — Variable Explorer\n\nBuild an interactive JavaScript variable scope visualizer:\n\n```html\n<!DOCTYPE html>\n<html lang="en">\n<head>\n  <meta charset="UTF-8">\n  <title>Variable Scope Explorer</title>\n  <style>\n    body { font-family: monospace; padding: 2rem; background: #1e293b; color: #e2e8f0; }\n    .scope { border: 1px solid #334155; border-radius: 8px; padding: 1rem; margin: 0.5rem 0; }\n    .global-scope   { border-color: #10b981; }\n    .function-scope { border-color: #3b82f6; }\n    .block-scope    { border-color: #f59e0b; }\n    .scope-label    { font-size: 0.7rem; color: #94a3b8; margin-bottom: 0.5rem; }\n    .var-item       { padding: 0.25rem 0; }\n    .keyword-var   { color: #f87171; }\n    .keyword-let   { color: #34d399; }\n    .keyword-const { color: #60a5fa; }\n    textarea { width: 100%; height: 200px; background: #0f172a; color: #e2e8f0; border: 1px solid #334155; padding: 1rem; border-radius: 6px; }\n    button { margin-top: 1rem; padding: 0.5rem 1rem; background: #3b82f6; color: white; border: none; border-radius: 6px; cursor: pointer; }\n  </style>\n</head>\n<body>\n  <h1>Variable Scope Explorer</h1>\n  <p>Enter JavaScript code with var, let, const declarations:</p>\n\n  <textarea id="code">\nvar globalVar = "I am global";\nlet globalLet = "Also global";\nconst GLOBAL_CONST = 42;\n\nfunction myFunction() {\n  var funcVar = "Function scoped";\n  let funcLet = "Also function scoped";\n\n  if (true) {\n    var blockVar = "I leak to function!";\n    let blockLet = "I stay in block";\n    const BLOCK_CONST = "Also in block";\n  }\n}\n  </textarea>\n  <button onclick="analyzeScope()">Analyze Scope</button>\n\n  <div id="output" style="margin-top:2rem;"></div>\n\n  <script>\n    function analyzeScope() {\n      const code = document.getElementById("code").value;\n      const lines = code.split("\\n");\n      const scopes = [{ type: "global", vars: [], children: [] }];\n      let currentScope = scopes[0];\n      const output = document.getElementById("output");\n\n      output.innerHTML = "<h2>Scope Analysis</h2>";\n\n      lines.forEach((line, i) => {\n        const trimmed = line.trim();\n        const varMatch = trimmed.match(/^(var|let|const)\\s+(\\w+)/);\n        if (varMatch) {\n          const [, keyword, name] = varMatch;\n          output.innerHTML += `<div class="scope ${keyword === "var" ? "global-scope" : "block-scope"}">\n            <div class="scope-label">Line ${i + 1}</div>\n            <div class="var-item">\n              <span class="keyword-${keyword}">${keyword}</span> ${name}\n              — <em>${keyword === "var" ? "Function/Global scoped" : "Block scoped"}</em>\n            </div>\n          </div>`;\n        }\n      });\n    }\n  </script>\n</body>\n</html>\n```\n\n**Extend it:**\n1. Highlight TDZ access errors\n2. Show what value each variable holds at each line\n3. Add a "Run" button that executes the code and shows output\n\n---\n\n## 15. Lesson Summary\n\n| Feature | var | let | const |\n|---------|-----|-----|-------|\n| Scope | Function | Block | Block |\n| Hoisting | Yes (undefined) | Yes (TDZ) | Yes (TDZ) |\n| Reassignable | ✅ | ✅ | ❌ |\n| Redeclarable | ✅ | ❌ | ❌ |\n| Object mutable | ✅ | ✅ | ✅ |\n| Use today | ❌ Never | ✅ When changing | ✅ Default |\n\n**The Golden Rule:**\n> Use `const` for everything. Change to `let` only when you need to reassign. Never use `var`.\n\nThis single rule eliminates an entire category of JavaScript bugs related to scope, hoisting, and accidental global variables.', 25, 1)
