UPDATE public.lessons SET content = E'# Promises — Mastering Asynchronous JavaScript\n\n---\n\n## 1. Introduction\n\nImagine you order food from Zomato. You do not stand at the door waiting — you do other things, and the food arrives eventually. That is exactly how Promises work in JavaScript.\n\nA **Promise** is an object that represents the eventual result of an asynchronous operation. It is the solution to "callback hell" — deeply nested callbacks that made async code unreadable and unmaintainable.\n\n> **Real-World Impact:** Every modern JavaScript API — `fetch()`, database queries in Node.js, file reads — returns Promises. React Query, Axios, Supabase client — all built on Promises. Understanding Promises is not optional for any JavaScript developer.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Learning Objectives\n\nBy the end of this lesson you will be able to:\n- Create Promises using the `new Promise()` constructor\n- Consume Promises with `.then()`, `.catch()`, `.finally()`\n- Chain multiple Promises\n- Use `Promise.all()`, `Promise.allSettled()`, `Promise.race()`, `Promise.any()`\n- Use `async/await` as syntactic sugar over Promises\n- Handle errors properly in Promise chains\n- Avoid the Promise constructor anti-pattern\n- Debug Promise-based code\n\n---\n\n## 3. Concept Explanation\n\n### Beginner Level — What is a Promise?\n\nA Promise is like a "ticket" for an async operation:\n\n```javascript\n// Creating a Promise\nconst myPromise = new Promise((resolve, reject) => {\n  // Async work here\n  const success = true;\n\n  if (success) {\n    resolve("Data loaded!");    // Fulfil the promise\n  } else {\n    reject(new Error("Failed to load data"));  // Reject the promise\n  }\n});\n\n// Consuming a Promise\nmyPromise\n  .then(result => console.log(result))    // "Data loaded!"\n  .catch(error  => console.error(error))  // If rejected\n  .finally(()   => console.log("Done"));  // Always runs\n```\n\n### Intermediate Level — Promise States and Lifecycle\n\nA Promise has exactly THREE states:\n\n```\n           resolve(value)\n PENDING ─────────────────> FULFILLED\n   │                        (then callbacks run)\n   │ reject(error)\n   └────────────────────> REJECTED\n                           (catch callbacks run)\n\nRules:\n- Promise starts as PENDING\n- Can only transition ONCE (pending → fulfilled OR pending → rejected)\n- Once settled (fulfilled/rejected), state NEVER changes again\n- .then() always runs on fulfilled\n- .catch() always runs on rejected\n- .finally() always runs (regardless of outcome)\n```\n\n### Advanced Level — Promise Chaining\n\nThe power of Promises is chaining — each `.then()` returns a NEW Promise:\n\n```javascript\nfetch("/api/users/1")\n  .then(response => {\n    if (!response.ok) throw new Error(`HTTP ${response.status}`);\n    return response.json();         // Returns Promise<user>\n  })\n  .then(user => {\n    console.log("User:", user.name);\n    return fetch(`/api/users/${user.id}/courses`);  // Returns Promise<response>\n  })\n  .then(response => response.json()) // Returns Promise<courses>\n  .then(courses => {\n    console.log("Courses:", courses.length);\n    return courses.filter(c => c.completed);  // Returns array (auto-wrapped in Promise)\n  })\n  .then(completed => console.log("Completed:", completed.length))\n  .catch(error => {\n    // Catches errors from ANY step above\n    console.error("Error in chain:", error.message);\n  })\n  .finally(() => {\n    setLoading(false);  // Always runs — perfect for cleanup\n  });\n```\n\n---\n\n## 4. Visual Learning\n\n```\nPROMISE LIFECYCLE\n\n new Promise(executor)\n        │\n     PENDING\n     /      \\\n resolve()  reject()\n   /            \\\nFULFILLED     REJECTED\n    │                │\n  .then()        .catch()\n    │                │\n  returns         returns\nnew Promise     new Promise\n    │                │\n    └────────────────┘\n           │\n       .finally()\n           │\n     (always runs)\n\n\nPROMISE CHAINING FLOW\n\nfetch(url) ─> Response Promise\n                │\n        .then(r => r.json()) ─> Data Promise\n                │\n        .then(data => process(data)) ─> Result Promise\n                │\n        .then(result => display(result)) ─> undefined Promise\n                │\n        .catch(err => handle(err)) ─> catches any above error\n                │\n        .finally(() => cleanup()) ─> always runs\n\n\nPROMISE COMBINATORS COMPARISON\n\nPromise.all([p1, p2, p3])\n  ✅ All succeed → returns [r1, r2, r3]\n  ❌ Any fail    → immediately rejects with first error\n  Use: When all results needed, any failure is total failure\n\nPromise.allSettled([p1, p2, p3])\n  Always resolves → [{status, value/reason}, ...]\n  Use: When you want all results regardless of failure\n\nPromise.race([p1, p2, p3])\n  Resolves/rejects with FIRST to settle\n  Use: Timeout patterns, fastest-server wins\n\nPromise.any([p1, p2, p3])\n  ✅ First success → that value\n  ❌ All fail      → AggregateError\n  Use: Try multiple sources, first working one wins\n```\n\n---\n\n## 5. Syntax Reference\n\n```javascript\n// CREATING PROMISES\n\n// Constructor\nconst p = new Promise((resolve, reject) => {\n  setTimeout(() => resolve("done"), 1000);\n});\n\n// Already resolved/rejected\nconst resolved = Promise.resolve(42);\nconst rejected  = Promise.reject(new Error("Oops"));\n\n// CONSUMING PROMISES\n\np.then(value => console.log(value))      // runs on success\n p.catch(err  => console.error(err))      // runs on failure\n p.finally(()  => console.log("done"))    // runs always\n\n// Chaining\nfetch(url)\n  .then(r => r.json())\n  .then(d => process(d))\n  .catch(e => handleError(e))\n  .finally(() => setLoading(false));\n\n// PROMISE COMBINATORS\n\n// All succeed or all fail\nconst [user, courses, settings] = await Promise.all([\n  fetchUser(id),\n  fetchCourses(id),\n  fetchSettings(id),\n]);\n\n// All results, never throws\nconst results = await Promise.allSettled([p1, p2, p3]);\nresults.forEach(r => {\n  if (r.status === "fulfilled") console.log(r.value);\n  else                          console.error(r.reason);\n});\n\n// First to settle (success or failure)\nconst winner = await Promise.race([apiCall(), timeout(5000)]);\n\n// First to SUCCEED\nconst data = await Promise.any([mirror1(), mirror2(), mirror3()]);\n```\n\n---\n\n## 6. Multiple Code Examples\n\n### Example 1 — Wrapping Callbacks in Promises\n```javascript\n// Before Promises, everything used callbacks\nfunction readFileCallback(path, callback) {\n  fs.readFile(path, "utf8", (err, data) => {\n    if (err) callback(err, null);\n    else     callback(null, data);\n  });\n}\n\n// Promisify: wrap callback in a Promise\nfunction readFilePromise(path) {\n  return new Promise((resolve, reject) => {\n    fs.readFile(path, "utf8", (err, data) => {\n      if (err) reject(err);\n      else     resolve(data);\n    });\n  });\n}\n\n// Usage\nreadFilePromise("./config.json")\n  .then(JSON.parse)\n  .then(config => console.log("Config:", config))\n  .catch(err  => console.error("Failed to read config:", err));\n\n// Node.js built-in promisification\nimport { promisify } from "util";\nimport fs from "fs";\nconst readFile = promisify(fs.readFile);\nconst data = await readFile("./config.json", "utf8");\n```\n\n### Example 2 — Parallel vs Sequential Requests\n```javascript\n// SEQUENTIAL — Slow (waits for each before starting next)\nasync function loadDashboard_SLOW(userId) {\n  const user     = await fetchUser(userId);     // 200ms\n  const courses  = await fetchCourses(userId);  // 300ms  (waits for user!)\n  const badges   = await fetchBadges(userId);   // 150ms  (waits for courses!)\n  // Total: 650ms\n  return { user, courses, badges };\n}\n\n// PARALLEL — Fast (all start immediately)\nasync function loadDashboard_FAST(userId) {\n  const [user, courses, badges] = await Promise.all([\n    fetchUser(userId),     // ─┐\n    fetchCourses(userId),  //  ├── All start at the same time\n    fetchBadges(userId),   // ─┘\n  ]);\n  // Total: max(200, 300, 150) = 300ms\n  return { user, courses, badges };\n}\n\n// PARALLEL with individual error handling\nasync function loadDashboardSafe(userId) {\n  const results = await Promise.allSettled([\n    fetchUser(userId),\n    fetchCourses(userId),\n    fetchBadges(userId),\n  ]);\n\n  return {\n    user:    results[0].status === "fulfilled" ? results[0].value : null,\n    courses: results[1].status === "fulfilled" ? results[1].value : [],\n    badges:  results[2].status === "fulfilled" ? results[2].value : [],\n  };\n  // Partial data is better than total failure!\n}\n```\n\n### Example 3 — Timeout Pattern with Promise.race\n```javascript\nfunction timeout(ms, message = "Request timed out") {\n  return new Promise((_, reject) =>\n    setTimeout(() => reject(new Error(message)), ms)\n  );\n}\n\nasync function fetchWithTimeout(url, ms = 5000) {\n  try {\n    const result = await Promise.race([\n      fetch(url),\n      timeout(ms),\n    ]);\n    return result.json();\n  } catch (err) {\n    if (err.message === "Request timed out") {\n      throw new Error(`API call to ${url} exceeded ${ms}ms`);\n    }\n    throw err;\n  }\n}\n\n// Usage\ntry {\n  const data = await fetchWithTimeout("/api/slow-endpoint", 3000);\n} catch (err) {\n  console.error("Failed:", err.message);\n}\n```\n\n### Example 4 — Retry with Exponential Backoff\n```javascript\nasync function fetchWithRetry(url, options = {}, retries = 3) {\n  for (let attempt = 1; attempt <= retries; attempt++) {\n    try {\n      const response = await fetch(url, options);\n      if (!response.ok) throw new Error(`HTTP ${response.status}`);\n      return await response.json();\n    } catch (err) {\n      console.warn(`Attempt ${attempt} failed: ${err.message}`);\n\n      if (attempt === retries) {\n        throw new Error(`All ${retries} attempts failed for ${url}`);\n      }\n\n      // Exponential backoff: 1s, 2s, 4s...\n      const delay = Math.pow(2, attempt - 1) * 1000;\n      await new Promise(r => setTimeout(r, delay));\n    }\n  }\n}\n\n// Usage\nconst data = await fetchWithRetry("/api/unstable-endpoint");\n```\n\n---\n\n## 7. Try It Yourself\n\n### Exercise 1 — Create Your First Promise\n```javascript\n// Task: Create a Promise that:\n// - Resolves with "Even" if a random number is even\n// - Rejects with "Odd" if a random number is odd\n// Then consume it with .then() and .catch()\n\nconst numberPromise = new Promise((resolve, reject) => {\n  const num = Math.floor(Math.random() * 10);\n  // Your code here\n});\n\nnumberPromise\n  .then(result => console.log("Result:", result))\n  .catch(error  => console.log("Error:", error));\n```\n\n### Exercise 2 — Parallel API Calls\n```javascript\n// Using JSONPlaceholder API, fetch these THREE endpoints in parallel:\nconst BASE = "https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com";\n\n// Endpoint 1: GET /users/1\n// Endpoint 2: GET /posts?userId=1\n// Endpoint 3: GET /todos?userId=1\n\n// Requirements:\n// 1. All three requests must run simultaneously (not one after another)\n// 2. If any fails, handle gracefully\n// 3. Display: user name, post count, completed todo count\n\n// Your solution:\n```\n\n### Exercise 3 — Promise Chain\n```javascript\n// Build a Promise chain that:\n// 1. Fetches user by ID\n// 2. Uses the user ID to fetch their courses\n// 3. Filters to only completed courses\n// 4. Returns the count\n// Handle errors at the end\n\nfunction getUserCompletedCourseCount(userId) {\n  // Your promise chain here\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n## 8. Common Mistakes\n\n### Mistake 1 — Forgetting to return in .then()\n```javascript\n// WRONG — chain breaks, next .then gets undefined\nfetch("/api/user")\n  .then(response => {\n    response.json();  // No return!\n  })\n  .then(user => console.log(user)); // undefined\n\n// CORRECT\nfetch("/api/user")\n  .then(response => response.json())  // Return the Promise\n  .then(user => console.log(user));   // Gets the user\n```\n\n### Mistake 2 — Nested .then() (Promise Hell)\n```javascript\n// WRONG — nesting defeats the purpose of Promises\nfetch("/api/user")\n  .then(r => r.json().then(user => {     // Nested!\n    fetch(`/api/${user.id}/courses`)\n      .then(r => r.json().then(courses => {  // More nesting!\n        console.log(courses);\n      }));\n  }));\n\n// CORRECT — chain flat\nfetch("/api/user")\n  .then(r => r.json())\n  .then(user => fetch(`/api/${user.id}/courses`))\n  .then(r => r.json())\n  .then(courses => console.log(courses));\n```\n\n### Mistake 3 — Missing .catch()\n```javascript\n// WRONG — unhandled rejection crashes the program\nfetch("/api/data")\n  .then(r => r.json())\n  .then(data => process(data));\n// If anything fails, error is silently swallowed!\n\n// CORRECT — always add .catch()\nfetch("/api/data")\n  .then(r => r.json())\n  .then(data => process(data))\n  .catch(err => console.error("Failed:", err));\n```\n\n### Mistake 4 — Promise Constructor Anti-Pattern\n```javascript\n// WRONG — wrapping an already-Promise function unnecessarily\nfunction getUser(id) {\n  return new Promise((resolve, reject) => {\n    fetch(`/api/users/${id}`)  // fetch already returns a Promise!\n      .then(r => r.json())\n      .then(user => resolve(user))\n      .catch(err => reject(err));\n  });\n}\n\n// CORRECT — just return the Promise chain\nfunction getUser(id) {\n  return fetch(`/api/users/${id}`).then(r => r.json());\n}\n\n// Or with async/await\nasync function getUser(id) {\n  const response = await fetch(`/api/users/${id}`);\n  return response.json();\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n## 9. Best Practices\n\n1. **Always add `.catch()`** on every Promise chain — never leave unhandled rejections\n2. **Return values in `.then()`** — without a return, the next `.then()` gets `undefined`\n3. **Keep chains flat** — avoid nesting `.then()` inside `.then()`\n4. **Use `Promise.all()` for parallel independent requests** — do not await them one by one\n5. **Prefer `async/await` for readability** — it is just syntax sugar over Promises\n6. **Avoid the constructor anti-pattern** — do not wrap existing Promises in `new Promise()`\n7. **Use `Promise.allSettled()` when partial failure is acceptable** — do not let one failure kill all\n\n---\n\n## 10. Real-World Usage\n\n### React Component Data Loading\n```javascript\n// At companies using React Query (Zomato, Freshdesk, etc.)\nfunction CoursePage({ courseId }) {\n  const { data: course, error, isLoading } = useQuery({\n    queryKey: ["course", courseId],\n    queryFn:  () => api.getCourse(courseId),  // Returns a Promise\n  });\n\n  const { data: modules } = useQuery({\n    queryKey: ["modules", courseId],\n    queryFn:  () => api.getModules(courseId), // Returns a Promise\n    enabled:  !!course,                        // Only fetch after course loads\n  });\n}\n\n// React Query is 100% Promise-based internally\n```\n\n---\n\n## 11. Interview Preparation\n\n**Q: What are the three states of a Promise?**\n> Pending (initial state, neither fulfilled nor rejected), Fulfilled (operation completed successfully), Rejected (operation failed). Once a Promise transitions from Pending to either Fulfilled or Rejected, it cannot change state again.\n\n**Q: What is the difference between Promise.all() and Promise.allSettled()?**\n> `Promise.all()` rejects as soon as any Promise rejects — you lose all results if one fails. `Promise.allSettled()` always resolves with an array of results for all Promises (each with a `status` of "fulfilled" or "rejected"), allowing you to handle partial failures.\n\n**Q: What is the difference between `.then(onFulfilled, onRejected)` and `.then().catch()`?**\n> When using `.then(onFulfilled, onRejected)`, the `onRejected` handler does not catch errors thrown by `onFulfilled`. Using `.then().catch()` makes the `.catch()` catch errors from both the original Promise AND the `.then()` handler.\n\n**Q: How does async/await relate to Promises?**\n> `async/await` is syntactic sugar over Promises. An `async` function always returns a Promise. `await` pauses execution until the Promise settles, then returns the resolved value (or throws the rejection). Under the hood, the JS engine converts `await` to `.then()` chains.\n\n---\n\n## 12. Knowledge Check\n\n1. What are the three states a Promise can be in?\n2. What does `.then()` return?\n3. When does `.catch()` run?\n4. When does `.finally()` run?\n5. How is `Promise.all()` different from `Promise.allSettled()`?\n6. What is the Promise constructor anti-pattern?\n7. Why must you return inside `.then()` for chaining to work?\n8. What is `Promise.race()` used for?\n9. How would you convert a callback-based function to return a Promise?\n10. If the first `.then()` throws an error, which `.then()` handlers below it will run?\n\n---\n\n## 13. Coding Challenges\n\n### Easy — Promise Timer\n```\nProblem: Create a function delay(ms) that returns a Promise\nthat resolves after ms milliseconds.\n\ndelay(1000).then(() => console.log("1 second passed"));\nawait delay(2000); // pause execution for 2 seconds\n\nBonus: Create countdown(n) that logs n, n-1, ..., 1 with 1 second between each\n```\n\n### Medium — Implement Promise.all\n```\nProblem: Implement your own version of Promise.all without using\nthe built-in one.\n\nmyPromiseAll([p1, p2, p3])\n  - Resolves with array of all values when all resolve\n  - Rejects with the first rejection reason if any reject\n  - Empty array → resolves immediately with []\n  - Must preserve order (result[0] = p1 value, etc.)\n\nTest cases:\nawait myPromiseAll([Promise.resolve(1), Promise.resolve(2)]) // [1, 2]\nawait myPromiseAll([Promise.reject("err"), Promise.resolve(1)]) // throws "err"\nawait myPromiseAll([]) // []\n```\n\n### Hard — Implement Promise with Cancellation\n```\nProblem: Create a cancellable Promise wrapper.\n\nconst { promise, cancel } = makeCancellable(fetch("/api/slow"));\n\npromise\n  .then(result => console.log(result))\n  .catch(err   => {\n    if (err.isCancelled) console.log("Cancelled!");\n    else throw err;\n  });\n\n// Cancel the request\ncancel();\n\nRequirements:\n- cancel() immediately rejects the promise with { isCancelled: true }\n- The original async operation is NOT aborted (that requires AbortController)\n  but its result is ignored after cancel()\n- Once cancelled, cannot be cancelled again\n```\n\n---\n\n## 14. Mini Project — Promise-based API Client\n\nBuild a complete API client class using Promises:\n\n```javascript\nclass ApiClient {\n  #baseUrl;\n  #token;\n  #timeout;\n\n  constructor({ baseUrl, timeout = 10000 }) {\n    this.#baseUrl  = baseUrl;\n    this.#timeout  = timeout;\n  }\n\n  setToken(token) { this.#token = token; }\n\n  #getHeaders() {\n    const headers = { "Content-Type": "application/json" };\n    if (this.#token) headers["Authorization"] = `Bearer ${this.#token}`;\n    return headers;\n  }\n\n  #request(method, path, body) {\n    const controller = new AbortController();\n    const timeoutId  = setTimeout(() => controller.abort(), this.#timeout);\n\n    return fetch(`${this.#baseUrl}${path}`, {\n      method,\n      headers: this.#getHeaders(),\n      body:    body ? JSON.stringify(body) : undefined,\n      signal:  controller.signal,\n    })\n    .then(response => {\n      clearTimeout(timeoutId);\n      if (!response.ok) {\n        return response.json().then(err => {\n          throw Object.assign(new Error(err.message || `HTTP ${response.status}`), {\n            status: response.status,\n            code:   err.code,\n          });\n        });\n      }\n      return response.status === 204 ? null : response.json();\n    })\n    .catch(err => {\n      clearTimeout(timeoutId);\n      if (err.name === "AbortError") throw new Error(`Request to ${path} timed out`);\n      throw err;\n    });\n  }\n\n  get(path)           { return this.#request("GET",    path); }\n  post(path, body)    { return this.#request("POST",   path, body); }\n  put(path, body)     { return this.#request("PUT",    path, body); }\n  patch(path, body)   { return this.#request("PATCH",  path, body); }\n  delete(path)        { return this.#request("DELETE", path); }\n}\n\n// Usage\nconst api = new ApiClient({ baseUrl: "https://api.rlearn.com" });\napi.setToken("your-jwt-token");\n\n// Fetch all courses\nconst courses = await api.get("/courses");\n\n// Create a course\nconst newCourse = await api.post("/courses", {\n  title:      "React Mastery",\n  difficulty: "Intermediate",\n});\n\n// Update a course\nconst updated = await api.patch(`/courses/${newCourse.id}`, {\n  title: "React Mastery 2.0",\n});\n\n// Parallel fetch\nconst [user, settings] = await Promise.all([\n  api.get("/me"),\n  api.get("/settings"),\n]);\n```\n\n---\n\n## 15. Lesson Summary\n\n| Concept | Key Point |\n|---------|----------|\n| Promise | Object representing future value — pending/fulfilled/rejected |\n| `.then()` | Runs when Promise fulfils; returns a new Promise |\n| `.catch()` | Runs when Promise rejects; also returns a Promise |\n| `.finally()` | Always runs after settled; good for cleanup |\n| Chaining | Each `.then()` returns a new Promise — keep flat, always return |\n| `Promise.all()` | All must succeed; fails fast on first error |\n| `Promise.allSettled()` | All results regardless of success/failure |\n| `Promise.race()` | First to settle wins (success OR failure) |\n| `Promise.any()` | First to SUCCEED wins |\n| async/await | Syntactic sugar over Promises — same underlying mechanism |\n\nPromises are the foundation of all modern async JavaScript. Whether you are fetching APIs, querying databases, reading files, or handling user interactions — Promises are working behind the scenes. Master them and you master asynchronous programming.', 25, 1)
